Introduction
Software development methodologies are essential frameworks that guide teams in planning, executing, and
delivering projects. Among the most widely adopted methodologies are Agile and Waterfall. These two
approaches differ in philosophy, workflow, flexibility, and adaptability to changes. While Waterfall is traditional
and linear, Agile is iterative, collaborative, and highly adaptive. Understanding the strengths and limitations of
each approach is crucial for selecting the right methodology based on project requirements, complexity, and
stakeholder expectations.
Why Agile?
Agile methodology emerged as a solution to the challenges posed by traditional linear approaches,
particularly in dynamic environments where project requirements may change rapidly.
Iterative Development
Agile projects are divided into small cycles called sprints, usually lasting 1–4 weeks. Each sprint delivers a
working part of the system, allowing early feedback.
Flexibility and Adaptability
Agile welcomes changes even in late development stages without disrupting the project.
Continuous Customer Involvement
Stakeholders participate actively throughout the project to ensure alignment with needs.
Early and Frequent Testing
Testing runs parallel with development, reducing risks and technical debt.
Enhanced Collaboration
Daily Scrum meetings improve communication and transparency within the team.
Value Delivery and Customer Satisfaction
Agile ensures continuous delivery of valuable features.
Example Use Case: A mobile app development company may release an MVP early and improve it through
user feedback in subsequent sprints.
Problems with Waterfall
Waterfall is a traditional linear methodology where each phase must be completed before moving to the next:
Requirements → Design → Implementation → Testing → Deployment.
Rigid Structure
Changes after phase completion are costly and difficult.
Delayed Feedback
Clients only see the product at the final stage.
Late Detection of Errors
Issues are discovered late, increasing cost and effort.
Limited Stakeholder Involvement
Customers are mostly involved at the beginning and end.
High Risk in Dynamic Projects
Unsuitable for projects with evolving requirements.
Example Use Case: Government systems with fixed specifications often use Waterfall.
